---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import InspirationCollage from '../components/InspirationCollage.astro';

const chapters = [
  {
    id: 'record-reflect',
    eyebrow: 'Chapter one',
    title: 'Record and reflect',
    intro:
      'These influences showed me that ordinary days become more useful—and more meaningful—when they are recorded in a form that can be revisited.',
    items: [
      {
        id: 'phil-von-stade',
        number: '01',
        category: 'Video',
        title: 'Phil Von Stade',
        subtitle: 'The spreadsheet life logger who made the idea feel real',
        src: '/images_webp/phil_von_stade.webp',
        alt: 'Phil Von Stade presenting a life-logging spreadsheet',
        href: 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w2yIGGxg52A',
        cta: 'Watch the video',
        reverse: false,
        paragraphs: [
          'I assumed that building a life log in spreadsheets was an unusually solitary idea until I found Phil Von Stade’s 2012 video. Seeing someone else preserve everyday life in a structured sheet made the practice feel less like an odd personal habit and more like a legitimate way to build memory.',
          'Other life loggers have pursued total capture through cameras, sensors, and constant recording. Phil’s approach reinforced what still works best for me: deliberately recording the parts of life that are useful to remember, compare, or understand.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'A spreadsheet can be more than a calculator. It can become a durable, searchable record of a life.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'See the data it helped inspire', href: '/stats/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'michael-phelps',
        number: '02',
        category: 'Article',
        title: 'Michael Phelps',
        subtitle: 'Journaling as disciplined self-observation',
        src: '/images_webp/michael_phelps.webp',
        alt: 'Michael Phelps journaling inspiration image',
        href: 'https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6131365/2025/02/20/michael-phelps-journals-to-find-the-best-version-of-himself-when-i-tried-it-the-results-surprised-me/',
        cta: 'Read the article',
        reverse: true,
        paragraphs: [
          'Learning that an elite athlete used journals to study himself reinforced the value of recording more than outcomes. A result tells you what happened; a journal can preserve the conditions, thoughts, routines, and decisions around it.',
          'Technology extends that practice. Structured entries can be searched, filtered, compared across years, and summarized without sacrificing the original record. That combination of reflection and analysis became central to LifeLoggerz.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'Reflection becomes more powerful when the original words remain searchable and the surrounding patterns remain measurable.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Explore the LifeLoggerz approach', href: '/about/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'quantified-self',
        number: '03',
        category: 'Community',
        title: 'Quantified Self',
        subtitle: 'Data for self-knowledge, not data for its own sake',
        src: '/images_webp/dailyvis.webp',
        alt: 'Quantified Self article screenshot',
        href: 'https://dailyvis.com/posts/quantified-self-why-i-track-my-life-in-data/',
        cta: 'Read the perspective',
        reverse: false,
        paragraphs: [
          'The Quantified Self community gave me a wider language for what I was building. Personal data could be used to ask questions, test assumptions, and uncover patterns that memory alone would miss.',
          'It also supplied an important boundary: collecting more is not automatically better. A variable earns its place when it helps preserve something meaningful, improve a decision, or make a pattern visible.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'The point of tracking is not to produce the largest dataset. It is to understand something that matters.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Browse the current statistics', href: '/stats/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'perfice',
        number: '04',
        category: 'App',
        title: 'Perfice',
        subtitle: 'A focused interface for everyday tracking',
        src: '/images_webp/perfice.webp',
        alt: 'Perfice life-tracking app screenshot',
        href: 'https://perfice.adoe.dev/',
        cta: 'Visit Perfice',
        reverse: true,
        paragraphs: [
          'Perfice demonstrates how approachable a purpose-built life-tracking app can feel. A clean interface lowers the friction between experiencing something and preserving it.',
          'For my own system, I still prefer Google Sheets because every formula, table, and automation remains visible and editable. Perfice nevertheless keeps the possibility of a more polished LifeLoggerz interface in view.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'The best tracking interface is the one that makes consistent input easy without hiding the user’s own data.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Use the current templates', href: '/templates/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'vegantechnomad',
        number: '05',
        category: 'YouTube',
        title: 'VeganTechNomad',
        subtitle: 'Proof that lightweight tracking can still change perspective',
        src: '/images_webp/vegantechnomad.webp',
        alt: 'VeganTechNomad YouTube channel screenshot',
        href: 'https://www.youtube.com/@VeganTechNomad',
        cta: 'Visit the channel',
        reverse: false,
        paragraphs: [
          'VeganTechNomad approaches life tracking through simple habits and lightweight reflection. Her work is a useful reminder that a system does not need hundreds of variables to help someone notice how they live.',
          'That contrast also helped define LifeLoggerz. My own system goes deeper because I want years of records to connect across routines, media, work, health, and memory—but depth should remain a choice, never an entry requirement.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'Start small enough to continue. Add depth only when the added detail proves useful.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Start with a template', href: '/templates/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'optimize-experiment',
    eyebrow: 'Chapter two',
    title: 'Optimize and experiment',
    intro:
      'Tracking became more than preservation when I began treating routines as systems that could be tested, refined, and sometimes left alone.',
    items: [
      {
        id: 'efficiency-is-everything',
        number: '06',
        category: 'Blog',
        title: 'Efficiency Is Everything',
        subtitle: 'Making the hidden cost of repetition visible',
        src: '/images_webp/efficiency_is_everything.webp',
        alt: 'Efficiency Is Everything website screenshot',
        href: 'https://efficiencyiseverything.com',
        cta: 'Visit the site',
        reverse: true,
        paragraphs: [
          'Efficiency Is Everything was one of the first sites to change how I thought about small recurring actions. Its breakdowns of food costs, task duration, and daily friction showed how tiny differences accumulate when repeated hundreds of times.',
          'That idea pushed me to automate repetitive work and remove avoidable decisions. I later learned the other half of the lesson: time saved only matters when it is returned to something worth doing.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'Measure repeated friction, remove what adds no value, and decide in advance what the recovered time is for.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Read how the system evolved', href: '/about/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'raptitude',
        number: '07',
        category: 'Blog',
        title: 'Raptitude',
        subtitle: 'Treating self-improvement as a series of experiments',
        src: '/images_webp/raptitude.webp',
        alt: 'Raptitude blog screenshot',
        href: 'https://www.raptitude.com',
        cta: 'Visit Raptitude',
        reverse: false,
        paragraphs: [
          'Raptitude encouraged me to treat changes in daily life as experiments rather than permanent declarations. Try something, observe what happens, keep the useful part, and discard the rest without turning the result into a moral verdict.',
          'That attitude appears throughout LifeLoggerz. The system is never finished, but it also does not need constant expansion. Iteration should solve a real problem, not become a hobby that consumes the life being optimized.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'A failed experiment is still useful when it tells you what not to carry forward.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Read more field notes', href: '/blog/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'visualize-preserve',
    eyebrow: 'Chapter three',
    title: 'Visualize and preserve',
    intro:
      'The final leap was realizing that a personal archive should not merely store records. It should make them inviting to revisit.',
    items: [
      {
        id: 'feltron',
        number: '08',
        category: 'Annual report',
        title: 'Feltron’s 2014 Annual Report',
        subtitle: 'Turning personal data into visual storytelling',
        src: '/images_webp/feltron.webp',
        alt: 'Feltron 2014 annual report screenshot',
        href: 'http://feltron.com/FAR14.html',
        cta: 'View the report',
        reverse: true,
        paragraphs: [
          'Nicholas Felton’s annual report showed me that collecting the data is only half the job. Design determines whether the patterns feel like numbers in a table or the story of an actual year.',
          'LifeLoggerz began in functional spreadsheets, but Feltron remains the standard that pushes the public project toward clearer graphs, stronger hierarchy, and pages that invite exploration rather than merely proving that the data exists.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'Visual design is not decoration added after the analysis. It is part of how the meaning becomes understandable.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'See the visual statistics', href: '/stats/' },
        ],
      },
      {
        id: 'ryot',
        number: '09',
        category: 'GitHub project',
        title: 'RYOT',
        subtitle: 'Treating media consumption as a browsable personal archive',
        src: '/images_webp/ryot.webp',
        alt: 'RYOT GitHub project screenshot',
        href: 'https://github.com/IgnisDa/ryot',
        cta: 'View the project',
        reverse: false,
        paragraphs: [
          'RYOT introduced me to the idea of organizing media as a visual archive rather than allowing books, albums, and art to disappear into separate apps and recommendation feeds. It also led me toward Raindrop as a practical source for cover galleries.',
          'That influence became the Books, Albums, and Art pages: public-facing records of what accompanied different periods of my life, designed to be browsed as well as counted.',
        ],
        takeaway:
          'A media log becomes more meaningful when it preserves not only a total, but the individual works that filled the time.',
        internalLinks: [
          { label: 'Books', href: '/books/' },
          { label: 'Albums', href: '/albums/' },
          { label: 'Art', href: '/art/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
];

const principles = [
  {
    number: '01',
    title: 'Record what matters',
    text: 'Preserve the details that memory compresses, rearranges, or loses.',
  },
  {
    number: '02',
    title: 'Automate repetition',
    text: 'Let the system remove routine work instead of becoming another source of it.',
  },
  {
    number: '03',
    title: 'Review for decisions',
    text: 'Data earns its place when it improves understanding or changes an action.',
  },
  {
    number: '04',
    title: 'Turn records into stories',
    text: 'Graphs, archives, and daily snapshots should make a life easier to see.',
  },
];

const structuredData = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'CollectionPage',
  name: 'Ideas That Shaped LifeLoggerz',
  description:
    'The people, projects, communities, and ideas that influenced the LifeLoggerz personal data and systems project.',
};
---

<Layout
  title="Ideas That Shaped LifeLoggerz"
  description="The people, projects, and ideas that shaped LifeLoggerz: personal data, experimentation, automation, and visual archives."
  wide
  hideTitle
  showViews={false}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline set:html={JSON.stringify(structuredData).replace(/</g, '\\u003c')}></script>

  <main class="inspirations-page">
    <header class="page-hero">
      <p class="page-eyebrow">The people, projects, and ideas behind the system</p>
      <h1>Ideas that shaped <span>LifeLoggerz</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-lede">
        LifeLoggerz did not emerge from a single productivity method. It grew from life loggers,
        designers, athletes, experimenters, apps, and communities that each revealed a different
        way to record and understand a life.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Explore this page">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="#idea-map">Explore the idea map <span aria-hidden="true">↓</span></a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/about/">About LifeLoggerz <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </header>

    <InspirationCollage />

    <div class="chapters">
      {chapters.map((chapter) => (
        <section id={chapter.id} class="chapter" aria-labelledby={`${chapter.id}-title`}>
          <header class="chapter-heading">
            <p class="chapter-eyebrow">{chapter.eyebrow}</p>
            <h2 id={`${chapter.id}-title`}>{chapter.title}</h2>
            <p>{chapter.intro}</p>
          </header>

          <div class="chapter-cards">
            {chapter.items.map((item) => (
              <article id={item.id} class:list={['inspiration-card', { reverse: item.reverse }]}>
                <a
                  class="inspiration-media"
                  href={item.href}
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  aria-label={`${item.cta}: ${item.title}`}
                >
                  <img src={item.src} alt={item.alt} loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
                  <span class="media-number" aria-hidden="true">{item.number}</span>
                  <span class="media-action" aria-hidden="true">Open ↗</span>
                </a>

                <div class="inspiration-copy">
                  <div class="card-meta">
                    <span class="card-number">{item.number}</span>
                    <span class="category-pill">{item.category}</span>
                  </div>
                  <h3>{item.title}</h3>
                  <p class="card-subtitle">{item.subtitle}</p>

                  <div class="card-paragraphs">
                    {item.paragraphs.map((paragraph) => <p>{paragraph}</p>)}
                  </div>

                  <aside class="takeaway">
                    <span>What I carried forward</span>
                    <p>{item.takeaway}</p>
                  </aside>

                  <div class="card-actions">
                    <a class="external-link" href={item.href} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                      {item.cta} <span aria-hidden="true">↗</span>
                    </a>
                    {item.internalLinks.map((link) => (
                      <a class="internal-link" href={link.href}>{link.label} <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
                    ))}
                  </div>

                  <a class="back-to-map" href="#idea-map">Back to the idea map <span aria-hidden="true">↑</span></a>
                </div>
              </article>
            ))}
          </div>
        </section>
      ))}
    </div>

    <section class="synthesis" aria-labelledby="synthesis-title">
      <header class="section-heading">
        <p class="page-eyebrow">The synthesis</p>
        <h2 id="synthesis-title">What these influences became</h2>
        <p>
          None of them supplied a complete blueprint. Together, they helped form four principles
          that now guide what I track, what I automate, and what I choose to publish.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="principle-grid">
        {principles.map((principle) => (
          <article class="principle-card">
            <span>{principle.number}</span>
            <h3>{principle.title}</h3>
            <p>{principle.text}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="closing-panel" aria-labelledby="closing-title">
      <p class="page-eyebrow">From inspiration to system</p>
      <h2 id="closing-title">These ideas became LifeLoggerz</h2>
      <p>
        I borrowed principles, adapted them to my own life, and built something different. That is
        the point: take what helps, discard what does not, and create a system that fits the life
        you actually live.
      </p>
      <div class="closing-actions">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/stats/">Explore the Data <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/templates/">Use the Templates</a>
        <a class="text-link" href="/about/">Read the About Page <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style is:global>
  /* This page is intentionally wider than a normal article.
     Override the generic BlogPost prose constraints at the exact wrapper level. */
  article.wrap.prose--wide {
    width: 100% !important;
    max-width: none !important;
    margin-inline: auto !important;
    padding-inline: clamp(0.55rem, 2vw, 1rem) !important;
  }

  article.wrap.prose--wide > .prose {
    width: 100% !important;
    max-width: none !important;
    margin-inline: 0 !important;
    padding-inline: 0 !important;
  }

  .inspirations-page {
    --ink: #0f172a;
    --muted: #475569;
    --line: rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.11);
    --surface: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.88);
    --green: #166534;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 1180px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .inspirations-page *,
  .inspirations-page *::before,
  .inspirations-page *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  .inspirations-page a {
    text-underline-offset: 0.18em;
  }

  .page-hero {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin: 0.5rem auto 2.5rem;
    padding: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.5rem) clamp(1.25rem, 5vw, 4.75rem);
    border: 1px solid rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.1);
    border-radius: 30px;
    background:
      radial-gradient(circle at 12% 8%, rgba(134, 239, 172, 0.36), transparent 31%),
      radial-gradient(circle at 88% 15%, rgba(147, 197, 253, 0.35), transparent 33%),
      linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.94), rgba(254, 249, 195, 0.68));
    box-shadow: 0 22px 58px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.1);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .page-hero::after {
    position: absolute;
    right: -4rem;
    bottom: -5rem;
    width: 15rem;
    height: 15rem;
    border: 1px solid rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.13);
    border-radius: 50%;
    content: '';
  }

  .page-eyebrow,
  .chapter-eyebrow {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--green);
    font-size: 0.77rem;
    font-weight: 900;
    letter-spacing: 0.13em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .page-hero h1 {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0.55rem auto 1rem;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: clamp(2.65rem, 7vw, 5.6rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.065em;
  }

  .page-hero h1 span {
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, #166534, #1d4ed8);
    -webkit-background-clip: text;
    background-clip: text;
    color: transparent;
  }

  .hero-lede {
    max-width: 790px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    color: #334155;
    font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 1.9vw, 1.26rem);
    line-height: 1.68;
  }

  .hero-actions,
  .closing-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .inspirations-page .button,
  .inspirations-page .external-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    min-height: 46px;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.35rem;
    padding: 0.72rem 1.05rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    font-weight: 850;
    line-height: 1.1;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: transform 0.18s ease, box-shadow 0.18s ease, background 0.18s ease;
  }

  .button-primary,
  .external-link {
    border: 1px solid #0f172a;
    background: #0f172a;
    color: #fff !important;
    box-shadow: 0 10px 22px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.16);
  }

  .button-secondary {
    border: 1px solid rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.18);
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72);
    color: #0f172a !important;
  }

  .inspirations-page .button:hover,
  .inspirations-page .external-link:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    box-shadow: 0 14px 28px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.18);
  }

  .chapters {
    display: grid;
    gap: 5.25rem;
  }

  .chapter {
    scroll-margin-top: 5.5rem;
  }

  .chapter-heading,
  .section-heading {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto 1.7rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .chapter-heading h2,
  .section-heading h2,
  .closing-panel h2 {
    margin: 0.35rem 0 0.65rem;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3.3rem);
    line-height: 1.02;
    letter-spacing: -0.045em;
  }

  .chapter-heading > p:last-child,
  .section-heading > p:last-child {
    margin: 0 auto;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .chapter-cards {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.35rem;
  }

  .inspiration-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 0.95fr) minmax(0, 1.05fr);
    align-items: stretch;
    overflow: hidden;
    min-height: 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 28px;
    background: var(--surface);
    box-shadow: 0 17px 45px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.085);
    scroll-margin-top: 5.5rem;
    backdrop-filter: blur(14px);
  }

  .inspiration-card.reverse .inspiration-media {
    order: 2;
  }

  .inspiration-card.reverse .inspiration-copy {
    order: 1;
  }

  .inspiration-media {
    position: relative;
    display: flex;
    min-width: 0;
    min-height: 100%;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    overflow: hidden;
    padding: clamp(0.5rem, 1.2vw, 0.9rem);
    background:
      radial-gradient(circle at 16% 10%, rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.16), transparent 38%),
      linear-gradient(145deg, #101827, #172033);
    text-decoration: none;
    isolation: isolate;
  }

  .inspiration-media::after {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    z-index: 1;
    content: '';
    background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(2, 6, 23, 0.2), transparent 42%);
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  .inspiration-media img {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 0;
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    min-height: 0;
    max-height: 620px;
    object-fit: contain;
    object-position: center;
    border-radius: 18px;
    box-shadow: 0 12px 28px rgba(2, 6, 23, 0.28);
    transition: transform 0.32s ease, filter 0.32s ease;
  }

  .inspiration-media:hover img,
  .inspiration-media:focus-visible img {
    transform: scale(1.035);
    filter: saturate(1.04);
  }

  .media-number,
  .media-action {
    position: absolute;
    z-index: 2;
    border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.45);
    background: rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.58);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    font-weight: 900;
    letter-spacing: 0.07em;
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
  }

  .media-number {
    top: 1rem;
    left: 1rem;
    display: inline-grid;
    width: 2.55rem;
    height: 2.55rem;
    place-items: center;
    border-radius: 999px;
  }

  .media-action {
    right: 1rem;
    bottom: 1rem;
    padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
  }

  .inspiration-copy {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: clamp(1.5rem, 3.6vw, 3.4rem);
  }

  .card-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.55rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.85rem;
  }

  .card-number {
    color: #64748b;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 900;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  }

  .category-pill {
    display: inline-flex;
    padding: 0.28rem 0.62rem;
    border: 1px solid rgba(22, 101, 52, 0.2);
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: rgba(220, 252, 231, 0.72);
    color: #166534;
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 900;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    line-height: 1;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .inspiration-copy h3 {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--ink);
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3.3vw, 2.75rem);
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: -0.045em;
  }

  .card-subtitle {
    margin: 0.55rem 0 1.25rem;
    color: #315cf6;
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  .card-paragraphs p {
    margin: 0 0 0.85rem;
    color: #334155;
    line-height: 1.68;
  }

  .takeaway {
    margin: 0.55rem 0 1.2rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.05rem;
    border: 1px solid rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.14);
    border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;
    border-radius: 0 16px 16px 0;
